  "prompt": "How do our rockets and satellites escape from space rocks?",
  "response": "Spacecraft and satellites use several methods to avoid space debris and potential collisions:\n\n1. Tracking and Prediction\n- Ground-based and space-based tracking systems monitor known space debris\n- Precise orbital calculations help predict potential collision paths\n\n2. Collision Avoidance Maneuvers\n- Satellites can use small thrusters to slightly adjust their orbit\n- NASA and other space agencies have protocols for moving spacecraft out of potential collision paths\n\n3. Shielding\n- Spacecraft have protective layers called \"Whipple shields\" that can help deflect or break up small debris\n- Critical areas have additional reinforced shielding\n\n4. Probability Management\n- Most space missions calculate and minimize collision risks\n- Some orbits are deliberately chosen to reduce debris interaction\n\n5. Active Debris Removal (emerging technology)\n- Experimental missions are being developed to remove large pieces of space debris\n- Techniques include nets, harpoons, and magnetic capture systems\n\nSpace agencies continuously monitor and track thousands of pieces of debris to minimize collision risks. While perfect avoidance isn't possible, these methods significantly reduce potential hazards.\n\nThe International Space Station (ISS), for example, performs several collision avoidance maneuvers each year to protect its crew and structure.",
